Yes — that is the better approach.

You should not hardcode every resource file name.
Use path-based and extension-based wildcard-style checks so all framework/static resources are skipped automatically.

Better fix

Replace the earlier resource helper with this version:

private boolean isFrameworkOrStaticResourceRequest(HttpServletRequest hsr) {
    String uri = hsr.getRequestURI();
    String servletPath = hsr.getServletPath();

    if (uri == null) {
        uri = "";
    }
    if (servletPath == null) {
        servletPath = "";
    }

    String path = (uri + " " + servletPath).toLowerCase();

    // 1. Framework resource containers / wildcard path matching
    if (path.contains("/javax.faces.resource/")
            || path.contains("javax.faces.resource/")
            || path.contains("/rfres/")
            || path.contains("/cfres/")
            || path.contains("/a4j/")
            || path.contains("/ips/js/")
            || path.contains("/ips/css/")
            || path.contains("/images/")
            || path.contains("/scripts/")
            || path.contains("/styles/")) {
        return true;
    }

    // 2. Any resource-style xhtml endpoints
    //    e.g. popupPanel.css.xhtml, status.js.xhtml, buttonBackgroundImage.png.xhtml
    if (path.matches(".*\\.(js|css|png|gif|jpg|jpeg|svg|ico|woff|woff2|ttf|map)\\.xhtml($|\\?.*)")) {
        return true;
    }

    // 3. Normal static file extensions
    if (path.matches(".*\\.(js|css|png|gif|jpg|jpeg|svg|ico|woff|woff2|ttf|map)($|\\?.*)")) {
        return true;
    }

    return false;
}

Why this is better

This covers all of these automatically:
	•	/IPSWeb/javax.faces.resource/...
	•	/cfRes/...
	•	/rfRes/...
	•	/a4j/...
	•	/ips/js/...
	•	/ips/css/...
	•	popupPanel.css.xhtml
	•	status.js.xhtml
	•	buttonBackgroundImage.png.xhtml
	•	future JS/CSS/image/font resources too

So you do not need to list every file.

Keep matchExcludePattern() like this

At the top of matchExcludePattern(...), keep:

nv.setBooleanValue(false);

if (isFrameworkOrStaticResourceRequest(hsr)) {
    return true;
}

And keep the rest of your XSS validation only for business requests.

Important reminder

The bigger fix still stands:
	•	Only set nv.setBooleanValue(true) for do / cmd
	•	Do not set redirect for every query string

Otherwise resource requests with query params will still get redirected and break.

Even simpler version

If you want to avoid matches(...), you can use a helper:

private boolean hasStaticExtension(String value) {
    return value.endsWith(".js")
            || value.endsWith(".css")
            || value.endsWith(".png")
            || value.endsWith(".gif")
            || value.endsWith(".jpg")
            || value.endsWith(".jpeg")
            || value.endsWith(".svg")
            || value.endsWith(".ico")
            || value.endsWith(".woff")
            || value.endsWith(".woff2")
            || value.endsWith(".ttf")
            || value.endsWith(".map")
            || value.endsWith(".js.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".css.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".png.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".gif.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".jpg.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".jpeg.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".svg.xhtml")
            || value.endsWith(".ico.xhtml");
}

Then:

private boolean isFrameworkOrStaticResourceRequest(HttpServletRequest hsr) {
    String uri = hsr.getRequestURI();
    String servletPath = hsr.getServletPath();

    if (uri == null) {
        uri = "";
    }
    if (servletPath == null) {
        servletPath = "";
    }

    String path = (uri + servletPath).toLowerCase();

    return path.contains("/javax.faces.resource/")
            || path.contains("javax.faces.resource/")
            || path.contains("/rfres/")
            || path.contains("/cfres/")
            || path.contains("/a4j/")
            || path.contains("/ips/js/")
            || path.contains("/ips/css/")
            || hasStaticExtension(path);
}

Use this version if your team prefers simpler readable code over regex.

Recommendation

I would use the second version if your team is conservative, because it is easier to explain in code review.

